<section xml:id="sec-angle-between-vectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Angle between vectors</title>

<p>
There is also a geometric formula for the dot product, which shows how the dot product of two vectors is 
related to the angle between them.
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-angle">
<caption>The angle between two vectors</caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale = 1.2]
    % Vectors
    \draw[vector,->] (0,0) -- (3.5,0.5) node[midway, below] {$\vect{u}$};
    \draw[vector,->] (0,0) -- (2.5,2.7) node[midway, left] {$\vect{v}$};
    \draw[vector,->,gray] (2.5,2.7) -- (3.5,0.5) node[midway, right] {$\vect{u} -\mathbf{v}$};

    % Angle \theta
    \draw[thick] (0.8,0.11) arc (0:38:0.92);
    \node at (1,0.5) {$\theta$};
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>

<theorem xml:id="thm-geo-form-dot-product">
  <title>(Geometric formula for the dot product)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v} \in \R^n</m>, and <m>\theta</m> be the angle between them. Then
<me>
\vect{u}\cdot \vect{v} = \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\cos\theta
</me>.
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<proof>
<p>
By the cosine rule (see <xref ref="fig-angle"/>),
<me>
\|\vect{u}-\vect{v}\|^2 = \|\vect{u}\|^2 + \|\vect{v}\|^2 - 2\|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\cos\theta
</me>.
Meanwhile, using Property 5 of the dot product,
<me>
\|\vect{u}-\vect{v}\|^2 = (\vect{u} - \vect{v})\cdot(\vect{u} - \vect{v}) = \|\vect{u}\|^2 - 2\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v} + \|\vect{v}\|^2
</me>.
Subtracting these formulas, we get <m>\vect{u}\cdot \vect{v} = \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\cos\theta</m>.
</p>
</proof>

<remark xml:id="rem-CS-proof-alt">
<p>
We can combine the geometric formula for the dot product with the fact that <m>\cos\theta \le 1</m>, to get
<me>
\vect{u} \cdot \vect{v} = \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\cos\theta \le \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|
</me>. 
Similarly,
<md>
<mrow>
-\vect{u} \cdot \vect{v} \amp  = (-\vect{u}) \cdot \vect{v}  = \|-\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\cos\theta \\
\amp  =\|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\cos\theta \le \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|
</mrow>
</md>
Therefore <m>|\vect{u} \cdot \vect{v}| \le \|\vect{u}\| \|\vect{v}\|</m>. This provides another proof of 
and a geometric interpretation of the Cauchy&#x2013;Schwarz inequality. There are two reasons that we presented 
the first, more complicated-seeming proof of the Cauchy&#x2013;Schwarz: part of that proof is used for the proof of 
the triangle inequality, and it gives a purely algebraic proof (without relying on properties of the <m>\cos</m> 
function).
</p>
</remark>

<definition xml:id="def-orthogonal">
  <title>(Orthogonal vectors)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Two vectors <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v} \in \R^n</m> are orthogonal if <m>\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v} = 0</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
Orthogonal vectors are perpendicular, since, if <m>\theta</m> is the angle between two nonzero vectors 
<m>\vect{u}, \vect{v} \in \R^n</m>, then <xref ref="thm-geo-form-dot-product"/> gives
<me>
\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v} = 0 \implies \cos\theta = 0 \implies \theta = \pi/2
</me>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-angle-vecs">
  <title>(Determining angles)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Determine whether the angle between <m>\vect{u} = [2, -1, 1]</m> and <m>\vect{v} = [1, -2, -1]</m> is acute, 
obtuse, or a right angle.
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
We have
<me>
\cos\theta = \frac{\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v}}{\|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|} = \frac{2+2-1}{\sqrt{4+1+1}\sqrt{1+4+1} } = \frac{3}{6} = \frac{1}{2}\gt 0,
</me>
so <m>\theta</m> is acute. In fact, <m>\theta = \cos\inv(\frac{1}{2}) = \frac{\pi}{3}</m>.
</p>
</solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-orthogonal-vecs">
  <title>(Determining orthogonality)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Find <m>k\in \R</m> such that <m>\vect{a} = [1, -1, 2]</m> and <m>\vect{b} = [k^2, k, -3]</m> are orthogonal.
</p>
</statement>
<solution>

<p>
If <m>\vect{a}\cdot\vect{b} = 0</m>, then
  <me>
  [1, -1, 2] \cdot [k^2, k, -3] = k^2 - k - 6 = 0,
</me>
which factorises to give <m>(k+2)(k-3) = 0</m>. Therefore, <m>k=-2</m> or <m>k=3</m>.
</p>
</solution>
</example>

